    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you've touched upon a critical aspect of pitot tube functionality. If the pitot tube gets blocked while the static port remains clear, the airspeed indicator can indeed be thrown into disarray. Here's what happens:\n\nThe pitot tube is responsible for measuring the total pressure of the airflow, which includes both the static pressure and the dynamic pressure due to the aircraft's motion. If the pitot tube becomes blocked, it can no longer capture the total pressure of the airflow. As a result, the airspeed indicator relies solely on the static pressure measured by the static port.\n\nIn this scenario, the airspeed indicator will not be able to provide an accurate reading of the aircraft's airspeed. Instead, it may display a zero or a stuck reading, indicating that the aircraft is not moving relative to the surrounding air. This is because the airspeed indicator needs both the total pressure (from the pitot tube) and the static pressure (from the static port) to calculate the dynamic pressure and, consequently, the airspeed.\n\nIf the pitot tube becomes blocked, it's crucial for the pilot to be aware of this and take appropriate action, such as using alternate airspeed indicators or relying on other instruments and visual references to maintain safe flight.",
